# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gunicorn-wsgi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] `fork()` is the name of the system call that the parent process uses to "divide" itself ("fork") into two identical processes.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] After calling `fork()`, the created child process is an exact copy of the parent except for the return value of the fork() call.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] This includes open files, register state, and all memory allocations, which includes the program's executable code.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] In some cases the two continue to run the same binary, but often one (usually the child) switches to running another binary executable using the `exec()` system call.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] When a process forks, a complete copy of the executing program is made into the new process.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] This new process is a child of the parent process, and has a new process identifier (PID).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] The `fork()` function returns the child's PID to the parent process.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] The `fork()` function returns 0 to the child process.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] This enables the two otherwise identical processes to distinguish themselves from each other.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] The parent process can either continue execution or wait for the child process to complete.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] The child, after discovering that it is the child, will most often then replace itself completely with another program, so that the code and address space of the original program are lost.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] This replacement is, however, a choice of the architecture one builds the given program on, and is therefore not an obligatory step in the child process' life.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] If the parent chooses to wait for the child to die, then the parent will receive the exit code of the program that the child executed.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] To prevent the child becoming a zombie the parent should call wait on its children, either periodically or upon receiving the SIGCHLD signal, which indicates a child process has terminated.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] One can also asynchronously wait on their children to finish, by using a signal handler for SIGCHLD, if they need to ensure everything is cleaned up.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] Here's an example of a signal handler that catches any incoming SIGCHLD signals and handles multiple concurrent signals received.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] When the child process calls `exec()`, all data in the original program is lost, and it is replaced with a running copy of the new program.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] Although all data are replaced, the file descriptors that were open in the parent are closed only if the program has explicitly marked them *close-on-exec*.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] This allows for the common practice of the parent creating a pipe prior to calling `fork()` and using it to communicate with the executed program.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] Microsoft Windows does not support the fork–exec model, as it does not have a system call analogous to `fork()`.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/fork-exec] The `spawn()` family of functions declared in process.h can replace it in cases where the call to `fork()` is followed directly by `exec()`.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/gunicorn] The **Gunicorn** "Green Unicorn" (pronounced jee-unicorn or gun-i-corn) is a Python Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) HTTP server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/gunicorn] It is a pre-fork worker model, ported from Ruby's Unicorn project.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/gunicorn] The Gunicorn server is broadly compatible with a number of web frameworks, simply implemented, light on server resources and fairly fast.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/gunicorn] It is often paired with Nginx, as the two have complementary features.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] A **server** is a computer or software system that provides data, resources, or services to other computers called "clients" on a computer network.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] This architecture is called the client–server model.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Servers can provide various functionalities, often called "services", such as sharing data or resources among multiple clients or performing computations for a client.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] A single server can serve multiple clients, and a single client can use multiple servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] A client process may run on the same device or may connect over a network to a server on a different device.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Typical servers are database servers, file servers, mail servers, print servers, web servers, game servers, and application servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Client–server systems are most frequently implemented by (and often identified with) the request–response model: a client sends a request to the server, which performs some action and sends a response back to the client, typically with a result or acknowledgment.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Designating a computer as "server-class hardware" implies that it is specialized for running servers on it.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] This often implies that it is more powerful and reliable than standard personal computers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] However, large computing clusters may also be composed of many relatively simple, replaceable server components.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The use of the word *server* in computing comes from queueing theory, where it dates to the mid 20th century, being notably used in Kendall (1953) (along with "service"), the paper that introduced Kendall's notation.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In earlier papers, such as the Erlang (1909), more concrete terms such as "[telephone] operators" are used.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In computing, "server" dates at least to RFC 5 (1969), one of the earliest documents describing ARPANET (the predecessor of Internet), and is contrasted with "user", distinguishing two types of host: "server-host" and "user-host".
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The use of "serving" also dates to early documents, such as RFC 4, contrasting "serving-host" with "using-host".
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The average utilization of a server in the early 2000s was 5 to 15%, but with the adoption of virtualization this figure started to increase the number of servers needed.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Strictly speaking, the term *server* refers to a computer program or process (running program).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Through metonymy, it refers to a device used for (or a device dedicated to) running one or several server programs.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] On a network, such a device is called a *host*.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In addition to *server*, the words *serve* and *service* (as verb and as noun respectively) are frequently used, though *servicer* and *servant* are not.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The word *service* (noun) may refer to the abstract form of functionality, e.g.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Alternatively, it may refer to a computer program that turns a computer into a server, e.g.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Originally used as "servers serve users" (and "users use servers"), in the sense of "obey", today one often says that "servers serve data", in the same sense as "give".
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] For instance, web servers "serve [up] web pages to users" or "service their requests".
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The server is part of the client–server model; in this model, a server serves data for clients.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The nature of communication between a client and server is request and response.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] This is in contrast with peer-to-peer model in which the relationship is on-demand reciprocation.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In principle, any computerized process that can be used or called by another process (particularly remotely, particularly to share a resource) is a server, and the calling process or processes is a client.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Thus any general-purpose computer connected to a network can host servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] For example, if files on a device are shared by some process, that process is a file server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Similarly, web server software can *run* on any capable computer, and so a laptop or a personal computer can host a web server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] While request–response is the most common client-server design, there are others, such as the publish–subscribe pattern.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In the publish-subscribe pattern, clients register with a pub-sub server, subscribing to specified types of messages; this initial registration may be done by request-response.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Thereafter, the pub-sub server forwards matching messages to the clients *without* any further requests: the server *pushes* messages to the client, rather than the client *pulling* messages from the server as in request-response.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The role of a server is to share data as well as to share resources and distribute work.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] A server computer can serve its own computer programs as well; depending on the scenario, this could be part of a *quid pro quo* transaction, or simply a technical possibility.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The following table shows several scenarios in which a server is used.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Almost the entire structure of the Internet is based upon a client–server model.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] High-level root nameservers, DNS, and routers direct the traffic on the internet.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] There are millions of servers connected to the Internet, running continuously throughout the world and virtually every action taken by an ordinary Internet user requires one or more interactions with one or more servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] There are exceptions that do not use dedicated servers; for example, peer-to-peer file sharing and some implementations of telephony (e.g. pre-Microsoft Skype).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Hardware requirement for servers vary widely, depending on the server's purpose and its software.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Servers often are more powerful and expensive than the clients that connect to them.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The name server is used both for the hardware and software pieces.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] For the hardware servers, it is usually limited to mean the high-end machines although software servers can run on a variety of hardwares.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Since servers are usually accessed over a network, many run unattended without a computer monitor or input device, audio hardware and USB interfaces.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Many servers do not have a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] They are configured and managed remotely.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Remote management can be conducted via various methods including Microsoft Management Console (MMC), PowerShell, SSH and browser-based out-of-band management systems such as Dell's iDRAC or HP's iLo.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Large traditional single servers would need to be run for long periods without interruption.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Availability would have to be very high, making hardware reliability and durability extremely important.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Mission-critical enterprise servers would be very fault tolerant and use specialized hardware with low failure rates in order to maximize uptime.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Uninterruptible power supplies might be incorporated to guard against power failure.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Servers typically include hardware redundancy such as dual power supplies, RAID disk systems, and ECC memory, along with extensive pre-boot memory testing and verification.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Critical components might be hot swappable, allowing technicians to replace them on the running server without shutting it down, and to guard against overheating, servers might have more powerful fans or use water cooling.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] They will often be able to be configured, powered up and down, or rebooted remotely, using out-of-band management, typically based on IPMI.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Server casings are usually flat and wide, and designed to be rack-mounted, either on 19-inch racks or on Open Racks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] These types of servers are often housed in dedicated data centers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] These will normally have very stable power and Internet and increased security.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Noise is also less of a concern, but power consumption and heat output can be a serious issue.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Server rooms are equipped with air conditioning devices.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] A *server farm* or *server cluster* is a collection of computer servers maintained by an organization to supply server functionality far beyond the capability of a single device.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Modern data centers are now often built of very large clusters of much simpler servers, and there is a collaborative effort, Open Compute Project around this concept.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] A class of small specialist servers called network appliances are generally at the low end of the scale, often being smaller than common desktop computers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] A mobile server has a portable form factor, e.g. a laptop.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In contrast to large data centers or rack servers, the mobile server is designed for on-the-road or *ad hoc* deployment into emergency, disaster or temporary environments where traditional servers are not feasible due to their power requirements, size, and deployment time.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] The main beneficiaries of so-called "server on the go" technology include network managers, software or database developers, training centers, military personnel, law enforcement, forensics, emergency relief groups, and service organizations.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] To facilitate portability, features such as the keyboard, display, battery (uninterruptible power supply, to provide power redundancy in case of failure), and mouse are all integrated into the chassis.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] On the Internet, the dominant operating systems among servers are UNIX-like open-source distributions, such as those based on Linux and FreeBSD, with Windows Server also having a significant share.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Proprietary operating systems such as z/OS and macOS Server are also deployed, but in much smaller numbers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Servers that run Linux are commonly used as Webservers or Databanks.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Windows Servers are used for Networks that are made out of Windows Clients.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In practice, today many desktop and server operating systems share similar code bases, differing mostly in configuration.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] In 2024, data centers (servers, cooling, and other electrical infrastructure) consumed 415 terawatt-hours of electrical energy, and were responsible for roughly 1.5% of electrical energy consumption worldwide, and for 4.4% in the United States.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] One estimate is that total energy consumption for information and communications technology saves more than 5 times its carbon footprint in the rest of the economy by increasing efficiency.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/server-computing] Concerns about data centers' environmental impact focus on their electricity demand and associated emissions, especially as AI workloads increase server and cooling requirements.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] The **Web Server Gateway Interface** (**WSGI**, pronounced *whiskey* or *WIZ-ghee*) is a simple calling convention for web servers to forward requests to web applications or frameworks written in the Python programming language.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] The current version of WSGI, version 1.0.1, is specified in Python Enhancement Proposal (PEP) 3333.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was originally specified as PEP-333 in 2003.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] PEP-3333, published in 2010, updates the specification for Python 3.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] In 2003, Python web frameworks were typically written against only CGI, FastCGI, mod_python, or some other custom API of a specific web server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was thus created as an implementation-neutral interface between web servers and web applications or frameworks to promote common ground for portable web application development.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] Between the server and the application, there may be one or more *WSGI middleware components*, which implement both sides of the API, typically in Python code.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI does not specify how the Python interpreter should be started, nor how the application object should be loaded or configured, and different frameworks and webservers achieve this in different ways.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] A WSGI middleware component is a Python callable that is itself a WSGI application, but may handle requests by delegating to other WSGI applications.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] These applications can themselves be WSGI middleware components.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] A full example of a WSGI network server is outside the scope of this article.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] Below is a sketch of how one would call a WSGI application and retrieve its HTTP status line, response headers, and response body, as Python objects.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] Details of how to construct the `environ` dict have been omitted.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-gateway-interface] Currently wrappers are available for FastCGI, CGI, SCGI, AJP (using flup), twisted.web, Apache (using mod_wsgi or mod_python), Nginx (using ngx_http_uwsgi_module), Nginx Unit (using the Python language module), and Microsoft IIS (using WFastCGI, isapi-wsgi, PyISAPIe, or an ASP gateway).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p02] Below are the latest statistics of the market share of all sites of the top web servers on the Internet by Netcraft.
[src:gunicorn-wsgi/web-server-p02] NOTE: (*) percentage rounded to integer number, because its decimal values are not publicly reported by source page (only its rounded value is reported in graph).
